{
  "text": "KDM3B is a H3K9me1/2 demethylase, and is highly expressed in hematopoietic cells [CITATION_1] . H3K9 methylation status is linked to heterochromatin formation and the silencing of target genes [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Herein, we attempted to elucidate the negative regulation of ANGPT1 transcription by KDM3B. Consistent with our previous microarray analysis, depletion of KDM3B increased the expression of ANGPT1. By reporter assay using the ANGPT1 promoter, it was found that ANGPT1 promoter activity was up-regulated when KDM3B was knocked down. The negative regulation of ANGPT1 by KDM3B was demonstrated to be independent of the H3K9 demethylase activity of KDM3B. There have been reports that G9a positively regulates the transcription mediated by various nuclear receptors through an HMTase-independent mechanism [CITATION_4] 19) . Previously, we reported that H3K9 HMTase G9a activates the transcription of p21 in p53-null H1299 cells independent of its HMTase activity [CITATION_5] . These reports, including the current study, indicate that there are different layers of regulatory networks in epigenetic modifiers, including HMTases and histone demethylases. It is also interesting that up-regulation of the ANGPT1 transcription level was independent of angiogenesis-related transcription factors such as JunB and GATA1, tested herein. Further studies will be needed to elucidate the fine mechanism of transcriptional regulation by KDM3B, including identification of the responsible transcription factors involved.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "34467131",
    "[CITATION_2]": "23740530",
    "[CITATION_3]": "4331863",
    "[CITATION_4]": "9209025",
